**Abstract:** Completed version (November 10, 1998) of "The Question of Truth" examining the correspondence theory of knowledge. Develops the thesis that all knowledge is ultimately practical and applicative, tracing how the illusion of speculative knowledge arises from objectifying statements meant for practical reference. Analyzes Helen Keller's language acquisition to illustrate the distinction between denotative and connotative meaning, and explains how Galileo's method demonstrates applicative rather than specular truth.
**AI Recommendation:** HIGH - Most complete version of a central theoretical document; supersedes truth-2 as the definitive statement of Monasterio's critique of speculative knowledge.

